				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">[quote="samxp"]</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">...
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Acutally quoting your whole response would just make this undo long....so anyone can just refer to your post.
<br />

<br />
Please learn to comprehend what it is your reading.  Your entire response to me was arguing against the fact that warr vs pal vs sk tanking is NOT equal.  If you re-read my post AT NO TIME did I EVER say they were!!  I simply stated that they SHOULD BE.
<br />

<br />
Moreover, I stated that they SHOULD be equal but not in the same way.  Upper Tier Mobs SHOULD be stunnable by Upper level stuns to allow paladins to tank as they do in lower tiers.  Stuns should NOT ONLY be used for aggro generation, but ALSO a VIABLE means of damage mitigation.  This is what I mean by damage mitigation.
<br />

<br />
Tanking is NOT just a measure of how many 2000+ dmg hits a person can take before dieing.  Measuring a characters ability to tank also has to take into account how many 2000+ dmg hits a person can avoid, as well as prevent.
<br />

<br />
By your definition of tanking:
<br />

<br />
[quote="samxp"]</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Tanking is the ability to physical to take damage from a mob. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Then a Warrior who can take 5 2000+ hits from a mob while preventing none (through stuns, avoidance, etc) is a better "tank" than someone else who may only be able to take 2 2000+ hits, but never get's hit.
<br />

<br />
I'm sorry, I would take a tank with 100% avoidance over a tank who only takes 20% of the mobs damage any day of the week.
<br />

<br />
Note: This example has NOTHING to do with holding AGGRO, but purely MITIGATING damage.  
<br />

<br />
Again let me restate my original quote for you:
<br />

<br />
[quote="samxp"]</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Tanking is not the ability to take physical damage, it is the ability to MITIGATE the damage a mob does WHILE keeping it focused on attacking ONLY YOU!!!  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Maybe I confused you by adding the bit abount keeping the mob focused on you.  So I'll rephrase my quote, while still saying the same thing (without the aggro portion)...
<br />

<br />
Tanking is NOT ONLY the ability to take physical damage, it is the ability to MITIGATE the damage a mob does.
<br />

<br />
Whether this be through physically taking the hits better (DI-1) or through preventing the damage (stuns) or though avoiding the damage (block, dodge, parry, riposte, etc...) is irrelevant.  ANY character who only takes 40% of the damage a mob puts out, and has the same number of HPs (reuardless of whether its a warrior, paladin, monk, or even mage) can be considered equal in terms of tanking ability alone (not accounting for aggro).
<br />

<br />
They will each take the same number of heals, at the same interval, to keep alive; while offering the same survivability.
<br />

<br />
And in reguards to your quote:
<br />

<br />
[quote="samxp"]</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> And duh, mitigate damage is part of taking how many damage. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
All I can say is .... of course it is...but mitigating damage is NOT 100% taking how much damage.  It ALSO includes avoidance and prevention.
<br />

<br />
Matter of fact just your quote above makes the SAME argument that I am making in reguards to your original quote.  Tanking is NOT purely about how much damage you can take.  It is about how much damage you can MITIGATE.  Note: Taking damage and Mitigating damage are two different sides of the same coin.
<br />

<br />
Now I will aggree that Defensive/Evasive/Riposte disciplines do play a LARGE part in mitigation.  I do agree that knights should have EQUAL ability to "improve" their mitigation through comparable means.  There are any number of ways to make this happen, so I won't go into details.
<br />

<br />
In closing, I am sorry if adding the portion reguarding "WHILE keeping it (the mob) attacking ONLY YOU" confused you, or made you think I was saying something I wasn't.  
<br />

